04987nam a22006615i 9780823295166DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20222006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232951667 a10.1515/97808232951662doi  a(DE-B1597)626439  a(OCoLC)1322124816  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0210002bisacsh1 aGoodman, Grant K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerica's Japan :bThe First Year, 1945–1946 /cGrant K. Goodman. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aWorld War II: The Global, Human, and Ethical Dimension00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tPreface -- t1. A Yen for Japan -- t2. My First Study of Japanese-My Matriculation at Princeton University -- t3. My Memories of the Army Intensive Japanese Language School-The University of Michigan -- t4. Practical Training-Fort McClellan and Fort Snelling -- t5. To the Front Lines in the Philippines -- t6. Meeting the Surrender Envoys -- t7. Our Landing in Japan -- t8. My Work as an ATIS Officer -- t9. Letters to General MacArthur -- t10. My Views of General MacArthur -- t11. My View of the Constitution -- t12. The Movements of Reform-The Dynamic and the Static -- t13. The Appearance of Emperor Kumazawa -- t14. The Yokohama Court -- t15. The Democratic Boom, the English Boom, and the Christianity Boom -- t16. Two Suicides -- t17. My Trip to Shanghai -- t18. The Mikado -- t19. Observing the Tokyo War Crimes Trials -- t20. Returning to America -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the few non-Japanese Americans trained to read, write, and speak Japanese, Princeton undergraduate Grant Goodman had a privileged position during World War II. As an Army lieutenant, Goodman served in the Philippines at the close of the war and in Tokyo as an intelligence officer on General Douglas MacArthur’s staff. Goodman translated thousands of letters, interviews, and other documents by Japanese citizens of all kinds, and came to know, as few Americans could, the “hearts and minds” of a defeated people as they moved slowly to democracy. This book is a not only a fascinating personal chronicle of Grant Goodman’s unique experience in Japan. Moving deftly between his role as an Army officer gathering essential information and as a young scholar fascinated by Japanese culture, he provides a vividly drawn portrait of daily life in occupied Tokyo.Here he looks back at signal events: Japan’s responses to occupation, the writing of the new constitution and the de-deification of the Emperor, the International Military Tribunal and the issue of Japanese war crimes, reactions by ordinary Japanese to American occupiers, and much more.September 2, 2005, marks the 60th anniversary of the Japanese surrender on the deck of the USS Missouri. First published in Japanese in 1986, America’s Japan is not only superb history. It is also a timely reminder of the realities of war and the responsibilities of victors and vanquished alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aSodei, Rinjiro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329516640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295166423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295166/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlis